-- Three-Month Euro Libor Reaches a 10-Month High of 0.76%, BBA Figures Show
-- Keith Jenkins
-- 2010-07-09T11:16:08Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-09/three-month-euro-libor-reaches-a-10-month-high-of-0-76-bba-figures-show.html

          
          
             The  rate  banks say they pay for
three-month loans in euros in London rose to the highest level
in 10 months, data from the British Bankers’ Association showed.  
 The London interbank offered rate, or Libor, for such loans
was at 0.76 percent, the most since Sept. 4, 2009, the BBA said
today. The rate was 0.752 percent yesterday. The euro Libor-OIS
spread, a gauge of banks’ reluctance to lend, widened to 19.3
basis points as of 12:05 p.m. in London, from 17.7 basis points
yesterday.  
 Three-month  dollar  Libor slipped to 0.527 percent, the BBA
said. The rate was 0.528 percent yesterday.  
 Three-month  Euribor  rose to 0.822 percent, the most since
Sept. 2, 2009, from 0.81 percent yesterday, according to data
from the European Banking Federation.  
